ntor%20young%20cricketers%20in%20the%20coaching%20camps%20he%20ran%E2%80%9D.%20As%20a%20result%2C%20he%20forsook%20the%20huge%20sums%20of%20money%20others%20like%20Sunil%20Gavaskar%20and%20Ravi%20Shastri%20have%20earned%20from%20cricket%20commentary.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EYoung%20cricketers%2C%20particularly%20those%20from%20the%20%E2%80%9Cmofussil%E2%80%9D%2C%20would%20often%20stay%20in%20Bedi%E2%80%99s%20home.%20On%20an%20occasion%20when%20the%20Indian%20cricket%20team%20and%20the%20Indian%20hockey%20team%20were%20in%20Bangalore%20at%20the%20same%20time%20and%20Bedi%20noticed%20that%20whilst%20the%20cricketers%20were%20in%205-star%20hotels%20the%20hockey%20team%20was%20put%20up%20in%20a%20modest%20dormitory%20in%20the%20Kanteerava%20Stadium.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EGuha%20says%3A%20%E2%80%9CBedi%2C%20perhaps%20the%20only%20Indian%20cricketer%20who%20would%20have%20recognized%20the%20injustice%20of%20it%20all%2C%20took%20them%20out%20for%20dinner%2C%20I%20believe%20more%20than%20once.%E2%80%9D%20Ten%20years%20later%2C%20when%20the%20hockey%20player%20Surjit%20Singh%20died%20in%20a%20road%20accident%2C%20Bedi%20quietly%20donated%20some%20of%20the%20proceeds%20from%20his%20benefit%20match%20to%20the%20hockey%20player%E2%80%99s%20family.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThis%20is%20a%20side%20of%20Bedi%20no%20one%20knew%20of%20until%20Guha%20brought%20it%20to%20the%20world%E2%80%99s%20attention.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ELet%20me%20make%20one%20more%20point.%20This%20time%20about%20Bishan%20Singh%20Bedi%E2%80%99s%20boldness%20in%20commenting%20on%20and%20criticising%20politicians%2C%20including%20the%20present%20Prime%20Minister.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EFirst%2C%20however%2C%20this%20is%20what%20Ramachandra%20Guha%20says%20of%20cricketers%20today%3A%20%E2%80%9CIt%20is%20one%20of%20the%20sad%20truths%20about%20Indian%20cricket%20today%20that%20the%20greater%20the%20cricketer%2C%20the%20more%20opportunistic%20and%20spineless%20the%20human%20being.%20Cricketers%20with%20fame%20and%20wealth%20always%20seek%20to%20stay%20on%20the%20right%20side%20of%20the%20administrators%20of%20the%20Board%20of%20Control%20for%20Cricket%20in%20India%2C%20always%20curry%20favour%20with%20politicians%2C%20and%20never%20take%20a%20stand%20on%20matters%20of%20personal%20ethics%20or%20political%20principle.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EBedi%2C%20in%20contrast%2C%20truly%20stands%20out%20because%20he%20spoke%20his%20mind%2C%20repeatedly%2C%20forthrightly%20and%20unconcerned%20about%20the%20consequence.%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1698918364000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02151308%2Fkt-ram-b.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fvideo%2Fvideo-bishan-singh-bedi-karan-thapar-ramachandra-guha%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22'Bishan%20Singh%20Bedi%20stands%20out%20because%20he%20spoke%20his%20mind%2C%20repeatedly%2C%20forthrightly%20and%20unconcerned%20about%20the%20consequence.'%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A10%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fvideo%2Fvideo-bishan-singh-bedi-karan-thapar-ramachandra-guha%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22A%20Poet%2C%20a%20Dictator%20and%20the%20Fragility%20of%20Human%20Memory%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02142307%2FStalin-Pasternack.jpg%5C%22%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EA%20Dictator%20Calls%3C%2Fem%3E%20%E2%80%93%20a%20book%20by%20Albania%E2%80%99s%20leading%20novelist%20and%20poet%20Ismail%20Kadare%20%E2%80%93%20is%20difficult%20to%20pigeonhole%20into%20a%20genre.%20It%20navigates%20the%20treacherous%20territory%20that%20demarcates%20fact%20and%20fiction.%20It%20is%20about%20the%20precarious%20nature%20of%20historical%20truth.%20It%20is%20also%20about%20the%20fraught%20and%20often%20dangerous%20relationship%20between%20poets%2Fwriters%20and%20tyrants.%20In%20Kadare%E2%80%99s%20words%2C%20%E2%80%9CHistory%20is%20usually%20reticent%20regarding%20what%20happens%20between%20poets%20and%20tyrants.%20The%20truth%20gives%20way%20to%20inventions%2C%20some%20memorable%2C%20others%20forgettable.%E2%80%9D%20This%20is%20a%20book%20about%20the%20fragility%20of%20human%20memory.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20immediate%20aftermath%20of%20the%20arrest%20of%20Osip%20Mandelstam%20in%20May%201934%2C%20Stalin%2C%20Moscow%20lore%20has%20it%2C%20had%20telephoned%20Boris%20Pasternak%2C%20probably%20in%20June%201934.%20The%20tyrant%20was%20in%20his%20lair%20in%20the%20Kremlin%20and%20the%20poet%20in%20his%20apartment%20in%20Moscow.%20The%20conversation%20lasted%20around%20three%20minutes%20and%20then%20Stalin%20hung%20up.%20When%20Pasternak%20tried%20to%20call%20back%2C%20he%20found%20that%20the%20number%20no%20longer%20existed.%20It%20had%20apparently%20been%20created%20in%20the%20Kremlin%20for%20that%20one%20phone%20call.%20The%20phone%20call%20created%20a%20stir%20in%20the%20literary%20circles%20of%20Soviet%20Russia.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIf%20one%20were%20prepared%20to%20believe%20what%20circulated%20in%20the%20literary%20circles%20and%20in%20the%20samizdat%2C%20then%20Stalin%20asked%20Pasternak%2C%20%E2%80%9CA%20little%20time%20ago%20the%20poet%20Mandelstam%20was%20arrested.%20What%20have%20you%20to%20say%20to%20that%2C%20comrade%20Pasternak%3F%E2%80%9D%20A%20flabbergasted%20and%20probably%20frightened%2C%20Pasternak%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%9CMandelstam%20and%20I%2C%20we%20are%20very%20different.%E2%80%9D%20Or%20words%20to%20that%20effect.%20Why%20did%20Stalin%20call%20when%20he%20could%20easily%20have%20summoned%20Pasternak%3F%20Why%20the%20need%20to%20know%20what%20Pasternak%20thought%3F%20Was%20there%20in%20the%20phone%20call%20an%20implied%20(or%20not%20so%20implicit)%20threat%20or%20warning%3F%20Such%20questions%20continue%20to%20persist%20not%20the%20least%20because%2C%20according%20to%20Kadare%2C%20there%20are%20at%20least%2012%20versions%20of%20this%20three-minute%20phone%20conversation.%20These%20versions%20come%20from%20various%20sources%20%E2%80%93%20from%20Isaiah%20Berlin%20(the%20famous%20Oxford%20don%20who%20was%20viewed%20with%20great%20suspicion%20by%20the%20Soviet%20secret%20police%20and%20who%20reputedly%20smuggled%20the%20typescript%20of%20%3Cem%3EDoctor%20Zhivago%3C%2Fem%3E%20out%20of%20Soviet%20Russia)%2C%20the%20poet%20Anna%20Akhmatova%20and%20other%20reporters%2C%20witnesses%20and%20so%20on.%20The%20evidence%20is%20mostly%20second%2Fthird%20hand%20and%20hearsay.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20Soviet%20regime%2C%20as%20has%20now%20been%20discovered%2C%20was%20scrupulous%20in%20keeping%20records.%20The%20archives%20do%20say%20that%20such%20a%20conversation%20between%20Stalin%20and%20Pasternak%20did%20take%20place%20on%20June%2023%2C%201934%3B%20it%20lasted%20between%20three%20and%20four%20minutes.%20%E2%80%9CAll%20the%20words%20said%20by%20each%20participant%20are%20clearly%20evidenced%20and%20preserved%2C%E2%80%9D%20Kadare%20tells%20us.%20Can%20we%20trust%20the%20archived%20version%3F%20Historians%20tend%20to%2C%20since%20archival%20evidence%20is%20the%20staple%20of%20the%20historian.%20But%20archives%20can%20be%20biased%2C%20be%20one-sided%20and%20even%20be%20manufactured.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20324px)%2085vw%2C%20324px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02141833%2F51QccnH-bvL.jpeg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22324%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02141833%2F51QccnH-bvL.jpeg%20324w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02141833%2F51QccnH-bvL-194x300.jpeg%20194w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-683146%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22500%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EIsmail%20Kadare%3Cbr%3E%3Cem%3EA%20Dictator%20Calls%3Cem%3E%3Cbr%3EHarvill%20Secker%2C%202023%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%20%3Cp%3EKadare%20begins%20with%20the%20archival%20version%20according%20to%20which%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20secretary%20made%20the%20call%20and%20announced%2C%20%E2%80%9CComrade%20Stalin%20will%20speak%20with%20you%20now.%E2%80%9D%20Stalin%20then%20came%20on%20the%20line%20and%20asked%20Pasternak%20the%20question%20quoted%20above.%20The%20latter%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%9CI%20know%20him%20only%20slightly.%20He%20is%20an%20Acmeist%2C%20but%20I%20belong%20to%20a%20different%20group.%20So%20I%20can%E2%80%99t%20say%20anything%20about%20Mandelstam.%E2%80%9D%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20retort%20was%2C%20%E2%80%9CWhereas%20I%20can%20say%20you%E2%80%99re%20a%20very%20poor%20comrade%2C%20comrade%20Pasternak.%E2%80%9D%20And%20abruptly%20terminated%20the%20call.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThis%20record%20announces%20an%20arrest%20even%20though%20it%20was%20already%20the%20talk%20of%20Moscow%20but%20gives%20no%20indication%20why%20Stalin%20wanted%20to%20talk%20to%20Pasternak.%20But%20most%20mystifying%20of%20all%20is%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20comment%20before%20he%20disconnected%20the%20line.%20What%20did%20he%20mean%3F%20We%20get%20a%20clue%20from%20the%20second%20version%20that%20Kadare%20narrates.%20It%20comes%20from%20the%20memoirs%20of%20Galina%20von%20Meck%2C%20who%20was%20Tchaikovsky%E2%80%99s%20great-niece%20and%20probably%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20lover.%20She%20recalled%20that%20at%20a%20gathering%20of%20poets%20where%20she%20was%20the%20only%20outsider%2C%20a%20very%20upset%20Pasternak%20had%20appeared%20and%20had%20blurted%20out%2C%20%E2%80%9CSomething%20awful%20has%20happened%20to%20me.%20Awful!%20And%20I%20behaved%20like%20a%20coward.%E2%80%9D%20He%20went%20on%20to%20tell%20the%20gathering%20about%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20phone%20call%20to%20him.%20According%20to%20Pasternak%2C%20as%20reported%20by%20von%20Meck%2C%20he%20had%20given%20the%20following%20fumbling%20reply%2C%20%E2%80%9CYou%20know%20best%2C%20comrade%20Stalin%2C%20it%20is%20up%20to%20you.%E2%80%9D%20In%20answer%20to%20this%2C%20Stalin%20said%20%E2%80%9Cwith%20a%20definite%20sneer%E2%80%9D%20(the%20words%20are%20von%20Meck%E2%80%99s)%2C%20%E2%80%9CIs%20that%20all%20you%20can%20say%20%E2%80%93%20when%20our%20comrades%20were%20in%20tight%20spots%20we%20knew%20better%20how%20to%20fight%20for%20them%E2%80%9D%20and%20then%20put%20the%20receiver%20down.%20Was%20Stalin%2C%20through%20a%20seemingly%20innocent%20question%2C%20trying%20to%20implicate%20Pasternak%3F%20What%20would%20have%20happened%20to%20the%20latter%20if%20he%20had%20spoken%20in%20%C2%A0solidarity%20with%20Mandelstam%20and%20had%20condemned%20the%20arrest%3F%20Historians%20could%20also%20ask%20%E2%80%93%20Kadare%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20%E2%80%93%20did%20Stalin%20fight%20for%20his%20comrades%3F%20He%20fought%20against%20them%20%E2%80%93%20think%20of%20Trotsky%20in%20exile%20from%20the%20late%201920s%20and%20of%20Zinoviev%2C%20Kamenev%2C%20Bukharin%2C%20Preobrazensky%2C%20Radek%20and%20others%20already%20in%20disgrace%20when%20he%20is%20being%20holier-than-thou%20with%20Pasternak.%20Stalin%2C%20Kadare%20notes%2C%20if%20one%20goes%20by%20the%20second%20version%2C%20is%20actually%20humiliating%20Pasternak.%20But%20why%3F%20Kadare%20is%20justified%20in%20saying%20that%20the%20second%20version%20deepens%20the%20fog.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThere%20is%20nothing%20new%20in%20the%20third%20version%20which%20is%20a%20tape%20recorded%20conversation%20between%20two%20literary%20personalities%2C%20one%20of%20whom%2C%20S.P.%20Bobrov%2C%20was%20known%20for%20his%20malice%20towards%20Pasternak.%20However%2C%20when%20the%20issue%20of%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20fear%20is%20broached%20one%20of%20them%20said%2C%20%E2%80%9CHe%20shouldn%E2%80%99t%20have%20been.%20However%20brutal%20Stalin%20may%20be%E2%80%A6still%E2%80%A6Stalin%20was%20the%20sort%20of%20person%E2%80%A6of%20course%20brutal%2C%20but%20still%E2%80%A6%E2%80%9D%20Kadare%20comments%2C%20%E2%80%9CThis%20accursed%20%60but%20still%E2%80%99%20was%20usually%20a%20prelude%20to%20a%20tentatively%20prettified%20portrait%20of%20the%20dictator%2C%20and%20a%20corresponding%20denigration%20of%20the%20poet.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20fourth%20version%20comes%20from%20Victor%20Shklovsky%2C%20another%20distinguished%20man%20of%20letters%2C%20who%20wrote%2C%20Pasternak%20%E2%80%9Chad%20correspondence%20with%20Stalin%2C%20talked%20to%20him%20on%20the%20phone%2C%20and%20didn%E2%80%99t%20defend%20Mandelstam%E2%80%9D.%20The%20words%20%E2%80%9Chad%20correspondence%20with%20Stalin%E2%80%9D%20inevitably%20raises%20the%20question%3A%20was%20there%20something%20more%20than%20a%20brief%20phone%20call%3F%20This%20version%20adds%20that%20Pasternak%20told%20Stalin%2C%20%E2%80%9CYosif%20Visarionovich%2C%20since%20you%20have%20phoned%20me%2C%20let%E2%80%99s%20talk%20about%20history%20and%20poetry.%E2%80%9D%20Stalin%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%9CI%20am%20asking%20you%20what%20they%E2%80%99re%20saying%20about%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20arrest.%E2%80%9D%20So%20Stalin%20was%20not%20seeking%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20reaction%20but%20to%20find%20out%20what%20%E2%80%9Cthey%E2%80%99re%20saying%E2%80%9D.%20This%20version%20goes%20on%2C%20%E2%80%9CHe%20said%20something%20else.%20Then%20Stalin%20said%2C%20%E2%80%9CIf%20they%20arrested%20friend%20of%20mine%2C%20I%20would%20bend%20over%20backwards%20to%20help%20him.%E2%80%9D%20Pasternak%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%9Cif%20that%20is%20what%20you%E2%80%99re%20phoning%20about%2C%20I%20have%20already%20bent%20over%20backwards.%E2%80%9D%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20parting%20shot%20was%2C%20%E2%80%9CI%20thought%20you%20were%20a%20great%20poet%2C%20but%20you%E2%80%99re%20just%20a%20big%20fraud.%E2%80%9D%E2%80%9D%20The%20conversation%20ended%20and%20Pasternak%2C%20according%20to%20this%20version%2C%20wept.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20fifth%20take%20is%20from%20Nikolai%20Vilmont%2C%20a%20person%20very%20close%20to%20Pasternak%20in%201934%20but%20was%20no%20longer%20close%20to%20him%20when%20he%20recalled%20the%20incident.%20Vilmont%20claimed%20he%20was%20having%20lunch%20with%20Pasternak%20when%20the%20phone%20call%20came%20at%20around%204%20pm.%20The%20latter%20refused%20to%20believe%20that%20the%20great%20man%20actually%20wanted%20to%20speak%20to%20him%20so%20he%20was%20given%20a%20number%20to%20call%20back.%20When%20he%20dialled%20the%20number%2C%20Stalin%20spoke%20to%20him%20directly%20and%20said%2C%20%E2%80%9CYou%E2%80%99re%20upset%20about%20your%20friend%20Mandelstam.%E2%80%9D%20Pasternak%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%9CWe%E2%80%99ve%20never%20been%20real%20friends.%20More%20the%20opposite.%20We%20have%20different%20opinions.%20But%20I%E2%80%99ve%20always%20dreamt%20of%20talking%20to%20you.%E2%80%9D%20Stalin%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%9CWe%20old%20Bolsheviks%20never%20turned%20our%20backs%20on%20our%20friends.%20And%20I%20don%E2%80%99t%20intend%20to%20talk%20to%20you%20about%20nothing.%E2%80%9D%20Vilmont%20could%2C%20of%20course%2C%20hear%20only%20hear%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20side%20of%20the%20conversation%20but%20he%20said%20that%20he%20had%20put%20down%20what%20Pasternak%20had%20told%20him.%20Once%20Stalin%20disconnected%2C%20Pasternak%20grabbed%20the%20phone%20to%20assure%20the%20former%20that%20Mandelstam%20really%20wasn%E2%80%99t%20his%20friend%20and%20that%20he%20hadn%E2%80%99t%20denied%20the%20friendship%20out%20of%20fear.%20But%20there%20was%20no%20reply%20from%20the%20number.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20308px)%2085vw%2C%20308px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02142004%2FIsmail_Kadare_portret.jpeg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22308%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02142004%2FIsmail_Kadare_portret.jpeg%20611w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02142004%2FIsmail_Kadare_portret-260x300.jpeg%20260w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-683147%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22356%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EIsmail%20Kadare.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%20%3Cp%3EAll%20the%20five%20versions%20do%20not%20show%20Pasternak%20in%20a%20good%20light.%20In%20the%20sixth%20version%20which%20comes%20from%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20wife%2C%20Zinaida%20Nikolayevna%2C%20a%20different%20light%20emerges.%20Zinaida%20relates%20that%20she%20was%20ill%20and%20in%20bed%20when%20the%20call%20from%20the%20Kremlin%20came%20through.%20According%20to%20her%2C%20when%20she%20heard%20her%20husband%20say%2C%20%E2%80%9CHello%20Yosif%20Visarionovich%E2%80%9D%2C%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20blood%20went%20to%20my%20head%E2%80%9D%20but%20her%20husband%20remained%20calm%20and%20%E2%80%9Cspoke%20to%20Stalin%20in%20the%20same%20way%20as%20he%20would%20talk%20to%20me%20or%20you.%E2%80%9D%20Zinaida%20went%20on%20to%20say%2C%20%E2%80%9CI%20realized%20from%20the%20first%20exchange%20that%20it%20was%20about%20Mandelstam.%20Borya%20said%20he%20was%20surprised%20at%20his%20arrest%2C%20and%20although%20there%20had%20been%20no%20great%20friendship%20between%20them%2C%20he%20valued%20his%20work%20writing%20as%20the%20work%20of%20a%20first-rate%20poet%2C%20and%20always%20recognized%20his%20merits.%20He%20asked%20Stalin%20to%20help%20Mandelstam%2C%20and%20if%20possible%20to%20release%20him.%20Borya%20spoke%20to%20Stalin%20plainly%20and%20directly%20without%20fine%20words%20or%20going%20into%20politics.%20I%20asked%20Borya%20how%20Stalin%20replied%20to%20his%20suggestion%20of%20talking%20about%20life%20and%20death.%20It%20turned%20out%20that%20Stalin%20said%20that%20he%20would%20talk%20with%20pleasure%2C%20but%20didn%E2%80%99t%20know%20how%20to%20arrange%20it.%E2%80%9D%20In%20this%20telling%2C%20Pasternak%20had%20thus%20spoken%20to%20help%20a%20fellow%20poet%3B%20he%20hadn%E2%80%99t%20been%20flustered%20or%20frightened%3B%20the%20line%20hadn%E2%80%99t%20been%20abruptly%20cut%3B%20and%20there%20had%20been%20no%20attempt%20on%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20part%20to%20call%20back.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20seventh%20version%20comes%20from%20the%20diary%20of%20the%20poet%2C%20Anna%20Akhmatova%2C%20who%20recorded%20that%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20wife%2C%20Nadezhda%20(Nadya)%2C%20following%20the%20arrest%20of%20her%20husband%20had%20sent%20a%20telegram%20to%20the%20Central%20Committee.%20Following%20this%2C%20Stalin%20gave%20orders%20to%20have%20the%20matter%20looked%20into.%20Then%20he%20called%20Pasternak.%20Akhmatova%20added%2C%20%E2%80%9CWhat%20followed%20after%20is%20very%20well%20known%E2%80%A6Stalin%20reported%20that%20instructions%20had%20been%20given%20for%20everything%20to%20be%20straight%20regarding%20Mandelstam.%20He%20asked%20Pasternak%20why%20he%20hadn%E2%80%99t%20intervened.%E2%80%9D%20It%20would%20appear%20from%20this%20that%20the%20reason%20for%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20phone%20call%20was%20to%20assure%20Pasternak%20that%20matters%20were%20being%20set%20right%20and%20this%20could%20have%20happened%20earlier%20if%20Pasternak%20had%20intervened.%20Three%20years%20before%20her%20death%20(she%20died%20in%201966)%2C%20Akhmatova%20somewhat%20altered%20her%20version.%20According%20to%20the%20later%20version%2C%20Stalin%20said%2C%20%E2%80%9CIf%20a%20poet%20friend%20of%20mine%20were%20to%20go%20to%20prison%2C%20I%20would%20move%20heaven%20and%20earth%20to%20save%20him.%E2%80%9D%20Pasternak%20replied%20that%20if%20he%E2%80%99d%20intervened%2C%20Stalin%20wouldn%E2%80%99t%20have%20agreed.%20Stalin%20then%20said%2C%20%E2%80%9CBut%20he%E2%80%99s%20your%20friend%3F%E2%80%9D%20At%20this%2C%20according%20to%20Akhmatova%2C%20who%20wasn%E2%80%99t%20present%20during%20the%20conversation%2C%20%C2%A0Pasternak%20%E2%80%9Cshrivelled%E2%80%9D.%20Stalin%20continued%2C%20%E2%80%9CBut%20he%E2%80%99s%20a%20great%20poet%2C%20isn%E2%80%99t%20he%3F%E2%80%9D%20Pasternak%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%9CThat%20isn%E2%80%99t%20so%20important%E2%80%A6I%E2%80%99ve%20wanted%20for%20so%20long%20to%20talk%20with%20you.%E2%80%9D%20%E2%80%9CWhat%20about%3F%E2%80%9D%20%E2%80%9CAbout%20life%2C%20about%20death.%E2%80%9D%20At%20this%2C%20Stalin%20put%20down%20the%20phone.%20Akhmatova%20believed%20that%20Pasternak%20had%20been%20deliberately%20evasive.%20It%20should%20be%20noted%20that%20there%20were%20rumours%20in%20Russia%20that%20Anna%20and%20Pasternak%20had%20been%20lovers%2C%20even%20may%20have%20been%20husband%20and%20wife.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20eighth%20version%20from%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20wife%20is%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20most%20sparse%2C%20not%20to%20say%20bleakest%2C%20account%20of%20the%20events%E2%80%9D.%20She%20wrote%2C%20%E2%80%9CStalin%20began%20by%20telling%20Pasternak%20that%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20case%20had%20been%20reviewed%2C%20and%20everything%20would%20be%20all%20right.%20This%20was%20followed%20by%20a%20strange%20reproach%3A%20why%20hadn%E2%80%99t%20Pasternak%20approached%20the%20writers%E2%80%99%20organizations%20or%20%60him%20personally%E2%80%99%20and%20why%20hadn%E2%80%99t%20he%20tried%20to%20do%20something%20for%20Mandelstam%3F%E2%80%9D%20According%20to%20Nadezhda%2C%20similar%20to%20Akhmatova%E2%80%99s%20diary%20record%2C%20Stalin%20did%20not%20call%20to%20seek%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20advice%20but%20to%20convey%20hopeful%20news.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20ninth%20version%20comes%20from%20the%20wife%20of%20the%20futurist%20poet%2C%20Sergey%20Bobrov%20who%20had%20himself%20recorded%20his%20version%20of%20the%20events%20(see%20the%20third%20version%20above).%20Bobrov%E2%80%99s%20wife%2C%20Maria%20Pavlovna%20Bogolovskaya%2C%20wrote%20she%20had%20gone%20to%20Pasternak%20to%20seek%20help%20for%20her%20husband%20to%20gain%20permission%20for%20a%20publication.%20On%20hearing%20the%20request%2C%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20face%20had%20%E2%80%9Cclouded%E2%80%9D%20and%20he%20had%20said%20he%20was%20unable%20to%20do%20anything.%20He%20had%20asked%20her%20if%20she%20knew%20about%20his%20conversation%20with%20Stalin.%20When%20she%20had%20said%20no%2C%20Pasternak%20had%20said%20it%20had%20been%20difficult%20for%20him%20to%20talk%20as%20there%20had%20been%20people%20in%20the%20house.%20When%20Stalin%20had%20asked%20him%20what%20he%20thought%20of%20Mandelstam%2C%20Pasternak%20told%20her%2C%20%E2%80%9CI%20can%E2%80%99t%20talk%20about%20something%20I%20don%E2%80%99t%20feel.%20It%20would%20be%20foreign%20to%20me.%20That%E2%80%99s%20what%20I%20said%20to%20him%2C%20that%20I%20couldn%E2%80%99t%20say%20anything%20about%20Mandelstam.%E2%80%9D%20By%20this%20account%2C%20Pasternak%20felt%20nothing%20for%20a%20fellow%20poet%20and%20therefore%20saw%20no%20need%20to%20stand%20up%20for%20him.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20tenth%20version%20is%20from%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20lover%2C%20Olga%20Ivinskaya.%20She%20recorded%20that%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20leader%E2%80%9D%20had%20spoken%20in%20a%20%E2%80%9Crough%20voice%20using%20%3Cem%3Eti%3C%2Fem%3E%20as%20he%20usually%20did%E2%80%9D.%20He%20had%20asked%20what%20the%20gossip%20was%20about%20Mandelstam%20in%20%E2%80%9Cyour%20literary%20circles%E2%80%9D.%20Pasternak%20had%20replied%2C%20%E2%80%9CThere%20was%20no%20gossip%2C%20because%20to%20have%20gossip%20you%20have%20to%20have%20literary%20circles.%20But%20there%20are%20no%20literary%20circles%20because%20everyone%20is%20scared.%E2%80%9D%20At%20the%20other%20end%20there%20was%20a%20long%20silence%20and%20then%20Stalin%20had%20asked%20Pasternak%20what%20he%20thought%20of%20%E2%80%9Cthis%20poet%E2%80%9D.%20Pasternak%20had%20replied%20that%20%E2%80%9Che%20and%20Mandelstam%20were%20poets%20going%20in%20totally%20different%20directions%E2%80%9D.%20Stalin%20replied%20in%20%E2%80%9Ca%20tone%20of%20contempt%E2%80%9D%2C%20%E2%80%9CSo%20you%20don%E2%80%99t%20know%20how%20to%20stand%20up%20for%20your%20friend.%E2%80%9D%20And%20put%20the%20phone%20down.%20At%20that%20moment%2C%20Pasternak%20confessed%20to%20Olga%20Ivinskaya%20%E2%80%9Che%20froze%20completely%E2%80%9D.%20The%20interesting%20detail%20here%2C%20as%20Kadare%20underlines%2C%20is%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20use%20of%20%3Cem%3Eti%3C%2Fem%3E%20%E2%80%93%20was%20it%20a%20sign%20of%20intimacy%20or%20of%20contempt%3F%20It%20is%20the%20only%20testimony%20that%20mentions%20this%20detail.%20The%20other%20detail%20is%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20comment%20that%20fear%20had%20obliterated%20literary%20circles.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20penultimate%20version%20comes%20from%20Isaiah%20Berlin%20who%20claimed%20that%20Pasternak%20had%20spoken%20to%20him%20twice%20about%20the%20conversation%20with%20Stalin.%20Berlin%20wrote%20that%20Pasternak%20had%20initially%20thought%20someone%20was%20playing%20a%20prank%20on%20him%20but%20was%20convinced%20only%20when%20Stalin%20came%20on%20the%20line%20and%20explained%20that%20it%20was%20indeed%20Stalin.%20The%20latter%20asked%20Pasternak%20if%20he%20had%20been%20present%20when%20Mandelstam%20had%20read%20his%20%E2%80%9Csquib%20in%20verse%E2%80%9D.%20Pasternak%20said%20that%20this%20was%20of%20no%20consequence%20but%20he%20was%20happy%20to%20be%20talking%20to%20Stalin%2C%20he%20had%20always%20known%20this%20would%20happen%20and%20that%20they%20should%20meet%20%E2%80%9Cto%20discuss%20some%20matters%20of%20extraordinary%20importance%E2%80%9D.%20Stalin%20asked%20whether%20Mandelstam%20was%20a%20fine%20poet.%20Pasternak%20replied%20as%20poets%20they%20were%20entirely%20different%2C%20he%20felt%20to%20inner%20rapport%20with%20Mandelstam%20but%20he%20valued%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20poems.%20According%20to%20Berlin%2C%20%E2%80%9CAs%20he%20related%20this%20episode%2C%20Pasternak%20plunged%20into%20metaphysical%20views%20about%20turning%20points%20in%20history%2C%20about%20which%20he%20wanted%20to%20talk%20to%20Stalin%20in%20a%20deep%20conversation%20of%20historic%20significance.%E2%80%9D%20Stalin%20ignored%20all%20this%20and%20repeated%20his%20original%20question.%20Pasternak%20too%20reiterated%20his%20desire%20to%20meet%20Stalin%20to%20talk%20about%20life%20and%20death%20and%20that%20such%20a%20meeting%20should%20not%20be%20put%20off.%20Stalin%20retorted%20with%2C%20%E2%80%9CIf%20I%20were%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20friend%2C%20I%20would%20know%20how%20to%20defend%20him%20better.%E2%80%9D%20Berlin%20added%2C%20%E2%80%9CThis%20entire%20story%20seemed%20to%20cause%20him%20great%20pain.%E2%80%9D%20Pasternak%20also%20told%20Berlin%20that%20when%20the%20phone%20call%20came%20only%20he%2C%20his%20wife%20and%20his%20son%20were%20in%20the%20apartment.%20This%20casts%20a%20serious%20doubt%20on%20the%20veracity%20of%20what%20Nikolai%20Vilmont%20(fifth%20version%20above)%20claimed.%20According%20to%20Vilmont%20the%20call%20had%20come%20at%204%20pm%20when%20he%20was%20having%20lunch%20with%20Pasternak.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%2012th%20retelling%20(if%20retelling%20it%20is)%20says%2C%20%E2%80%9CThe%20tyrant%20was%20having%20fun%E2%80%A6%E2%80%9D%20The%20author%20of%20this%20was%20the%20writer%20Vladimir%20Solovyev%20who%20was%20suspected%20of%20being%20a%20KGB%20agent%20and%20admitted%20to%20being%20one%20in%201992.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EWhat%20is%20one%20to%20make%20of%20all%20this%3F%20It%20is%20too%20convenient%20to%20dismiss%20the%20episode%20and%20its%20many%20versions%20as%20a%20needless%20brouhaha.%20As%20students%20of%20history%20and%20of%20literature%20one%20cannot%20take%20such%20an%20evasive%20attitude.%20And%20Kadare%20doesn%E2%80%99t.%20He%20presents%20it%20as%20a%20riddle%20and%20interweaves%20it%20with%20many%20aspects%20of%20Russian%20and%20Soviet%20history%20and%20literature%20and%20his%20own%20dreams%20and%20nightmares%20about%20living%20under%20a%20communist%20dictatorship%20in%20Albania.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20overwhelming%20question%20is%3A%20why%20did%20Stalin%20call%20Pasternak%3F%20There%20are%20two%20different%20answers%20that%20emerge.%20One%2C%20Stalin%20was%20probing%20%E2%80%93%20gossip%20in%20literary%20circles%20and%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20own%20position%20regarding%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20arrest.%20And%20second%2C%20Stalin%20was%20passing%20on%20the%20information%20that%20he%20was%20setting%20things%20all%20right%20in%20the%20Mandelstam%20affair.%20There%20is%20one%20thing%20common%20to%20both%3A%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20chiding%20of%20Pasternak%20or%20sneering%20at%20him%20for%20not%20standing%20up%20for%20a%20fellow%20poet%2Ffriend%20and%20for%20not%20interceding%20on%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20behalf%20directly%20with%20Stalin.%20Only%20in%20the%20version%20given%20by%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20wife%20is%20it%20said%2C%20that%20Pasternak%20asked%20Stalin%20to%20help%20Mandelstam.%20A%20related%20question%20refuses%20to%20go%20away%2C%20what%20was%20the%20reason%20for%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20remorse%20%E2%80%93%20he%20wept%2C%20he%20froze%2C%20felt%20pain%2C%20%E2%80%9CI%20have%20behaved%20like%20a%20coward%E2%80%9D%20and%20so%20on.%20Was%20it%20because%20he%20felt%20he%20had%20failed%20to%20help%20Mandelstam%20(then%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20wife%E2%80%99s%20version%20goes%20through%20the%20trapdoor)%20or%20because%20he%20felt%20he%20had%20been%20humiliated%20by%20Stalin%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20issue%20of%20humiliation%20raises%20the%20question%20of%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20relationship%20with%20Stalin.%20Did%20they%20personally%20know%20each%20other%3F%20Hence%20the%20phone%20call%3F%20Why%20did%20Stalin%20use%20the%20familiar%20%3Cem%3Eti%3C%2Fem%3E%3F%20Recall%20also%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20wife%E2%80%99s%20testimony%20that%20Pasternak%20spoke%20to%20Stalin%20as%20an%20equal.%20One%20version%20states%20that%20Pasternak%20had%20some%20correspondence%20with%20Stalin.%20This%20question%20acquires%20some%20importance%20because%20as%20Kadare%20informs%20us%20that%20in%201935%2C%20Pasternak%20had%20actually%20written%20to%20Stalin%20to%20release%20Anna%20Akhmatova%E2%80%99s%20husband%20and%20her%20son.%20This%20would%20suggest%20that%20he%20had%20some%20kind%20of%20access%20to%20Stalin.%20This%20also%20adds%20credibility%20to%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20reproach%20about%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20failure%20to%20intercede%20on%20behalf%20of%20Mandelstam%20in%201934.%20When%20Pasternak%20did%20intervene%20in%201935%2C%20on%20behalf%20of%20Akhmatova%2C%20Stalin%20responded%20positively.%20It%20also%20should%20be%20noted%2C%20as%20Kadare%20does%2C%20that%20Stalin%20was%20true%20to%20his%20word%20and%20he%20did%20release%20Mandelstam%20in%201934%20and%20the%20latter%20went%20and%20met%20Pasternak.%20But%20Pasternak%20said%20and%20did%20nothing%20when%20Mandelstam%20was%20arrested%20a%20second%20time%20in%201938%20and%20sent%20to%20the%20Gulag%20where%20he%20died.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20question%20of%20a%20personal%20equation%20between%20the%20poet%20and%20the%20dictator%20gets%20a%20different%20dimension%20with%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20plea%20to%20discuss%20philosophical%20issues%20%E2%80%93%20life%20and%20death%2C%20turning%20points%20in%20history%20%E2%80%93%20with%20Stalin.%20This%20request%20is%20odd%20because%20it%20was%20well%20known%20in%20Bolshevik%2Fcommunist%20circles%20that%20philosophy%20was%20not%20Koba%E2%80%99s%20(as%20Stalin%20was%20fondly%20called%20by%20his%20comrades)%20strong%20suit.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20context%20of%20the%20relationship%20between%20Pasternak%20and%20Stalin%20it%20is%20worth%20recalling%20an%20anecdote%20that%20Kadare%20does%20not%20include.%20It%20was%20said%20that%20Pasternak%20had%20translated%20some%20well-known%20Georgian%20poets.%20Stalin%20had%20approved%20of%20those%20translations.%20And%20later%2C%20when%20Stalin%20found%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20name%20on%20a%20death%20list%20%E2%80%93%20it%20was%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20practice%20to%20personally%20go%20through%20death%20lists%20and%20sign%20them%20%E2%80%93%20he%20put%20his%20pen%20through%20Pasternak%E2%80%99s%20name.%20His%20instructions%20were%2C%20%E2%80%9CDon%E2%80%99t%20touch%20the%20cloud%20gatherer.%E2%80%9D%20He%20did%20not%20do%20the%20same%20for%20writers%20like%20Isaac%20Babel%20or%20even%20for%20the%20Georgian%20poet%2C%20Titzian%20Tabidze.%20It%20is%20not%20unreasonable%20to%20assume%20that%20there%20must%20have%20been%20some%20affinity%20between%20the%20dictator%20and%20the%20poet.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThere%20are%20no%20easy%20answers.%20In%20Kadare%E2%80%99s%20words%2C%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20incident%20impresses%20upon%20us%20its%20impossibility.%20It%20strikes%20an%20alarm%20bell%20that%20will%20not%20let%20any%20human%20conscience%20rest%20easy.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ETyrants%20will%20always%20have%20their%20perverse%20fun%20playing%20in%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20zone%20of%20death%E2%80%9D%20(Kadare%E2%80%99s%20telling%20phrase)%20but%20poets%20even%20when%20they%20perish%20in%20the%20Gulag%20or%20reach%20for%20the%20phone%20hoping%20to%20call%20the%20tyrant%20have%20immortality%20thrust%20on%20them.%20Nadezhda%20Mandelstam%E2%80%99s%20memoir%20is%20called%20%3Cem%3EHope%20Against%20Hope%3C%2Fem%3E.%20Poets%20kindle%20hope.%20Tyrants%20breed%20despair.%20Thus%2C%20poets%2C%20Kadare%E2%80%99s%20writes%2C%20are%20%E2%80%9Cwithout%20end%E2%80%9D.%20In%20the%20words%20of%20Ecclesiasticus%20(44%3A15)%2C%20%E2%80%9CThe%20people%20will%20tell%20of%20their%20wisdom%2C%20and%20the%20congregation%20will%20shew%20forth%20their%20praise.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fm.thewire.in%2Fbyline%2Frudrangshu-mukherjee%5C%22%3ERudrangshu%20Mukherjee%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0is%20chancellor%20and%20professor%20of%20History%20at%20Ashoka%20University.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1698918007000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F11%2F02142307%2FStalin-Pasternack.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fbooks%2Fa-poet-a-dictator-and-the-fragility-of-human-memory%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Ismail%20Kadare's%20'A%20Dictator%20Calls'%20brings%20out%20the%20fraught%20and%20often%20dangerous%20relationship%20between%20poets%2Fwriters%20and%20tyrants.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A3%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fbooks%2Fa-poet-a-dictator-and-the-fragility-of-human-memory%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Harris%20and%20Sunak%20due%20to%20discuss%20cutting-edge%20AI%20risks%20at%20UK%20summit%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%22%2C%22published%22%3A169891780300